name: Tannhäuser Ouvertüre
comments: "Tannhäuser" (full title: "Tannhäuser und der Sängerkrieg auf Wartburg", WWV 70) is Wagner's fifth opera. Centering around a mythologized Minnesänger (medieval singer/poet) and a 13th century singers contest at castle Wartburg, it was first perfomed at Königliches Hoftheater, Dresden, on October 19, 1845 (conducted by Wagner himself). The ouverture is often performed as a stand-alone work, first so by Gewandhausorchester Leipzig (conducted by Felix Mendelssohn) in February, 1846,

name: Pacific 231
comments: This is the first of Honegger's three symphonic movements. He soon changed the working title "Mouvement Symphonique" and named the work according to what it was - a musical dedication to a steam locomotive (2-3-1 relates to steam locomotives' number of axles). The work premiered on 8th May, 1924, at l'Opera nationale de Paris (conducted by Serge Koussevtizky), In 1949, it was used as the theme for a same-named short film and awarded the "Palme d'or du court métrage" at the Cannes festival.

name: Das Wandern ist des Müllers Lust [poem]
comments: "To wander is the miller's delight" is the first line of a poem by Wilhelm Müller written in 1821 with the title "Wanderschaft" as part of a collection "Die schöne Müllerin". The poem was set to music often notably by Franz Schubert in 1823 titled "Das Wandern" as part of his song cycle "Die schöne Müllerin" and by Carl Friedrich Zöllner, who wrote a four-part setting in 1844. With his melody, the poem became a popular German Wanderlied and Volkslied.
